Opening tomorrow in Milan, the exhibition 'Heimat. A Sense of Belonging' focuses on both emblematic and lesser known aspects of Lindbergh’s work.
This new installation unfolds in three chapters on the ground floor of Armani/Silos. Peter's unique viewpoint, his idea of space and beauty and his unmistakable aesthetics are revealed, together with the sources of inspiration, in a journey that goes beyond the idea of fashion photography, starting with the portraits of ‘The Naked Truth’, expanding with the powerful ambiances of ‘Heimat’, settling with the startling rawness of ‘The Modern Heroine’.
'Heimat. A Sense of Belonging' is curated by Giorgio Armani and the Peter Lindbergh Foundation.
 ARMANI/SILOS 22 February - 2 August 2020
Via Bergognone 40, Milano

A new exhibition, entitled 'Heimat. A Sense of Belonging', pays homage to the powerful affinities between Giorgio Armani and Peter Lindbergh, two visionaries whose unique sense of identity has set very personal standards, in art as well as in life. 
Lindbergh’s understanding of femininity, his interest in personality and proclivity for truth have always set him apart among his peers. There is an inherent honesty to Lindbergh’s work that is closely linked to his own 'Heimat'.
The German word 'Heimat' means more than home: it is a place of the heart; it is where one belongs.
- ARMANI/SILOS, MILAN 22 February - 2 August 2020

Thank you to everyone present for the opening of the exhibition 'Peter Lindbergh. Untold Stories' last week in Düsseldorf.

We wish to thank Kunstpalast’s Director Felix Krämer for his enthusiasm and confidence in granting Peter absolute freedom to conceive and mature this unprecedented, self-curated exhibition.

A warm thank you to his whole team and particularly to Felicity Korn and Stefanie Hennig for their valuable advice and attentive guidance in turning Peter’s 'inner voice' to reality.

Wim & Donata Wenders for their enduring friendship and inspiring words.

Special thanks to Benedikt Taschen, Marlene and Charlotte Taschen, Veronica Weller, Simone Philippi, and Frank Goerhardt.
-
'Peter Lindbergh. Untold Stories' is organised by the @kunstpalast, Düsseldorf and will next be presented at the Museum für Kunst und Gewerbe, Hamburg (Summer 2020), the Hessisches Landesmuseum, Darmstadt (Fall 2020) and to MADRE in Naples (Spring 2021)

Opening on February 5th, 'Peter Lindbergh: Untold Stories' is the first ever survey exhibition curated by Peter himself. 'Untold Stories' will celebrate the photographer's legacy while showcasing his highly personal approach. Lindbergh's comprehension of fashion photography was that it can - and should - exist very well without putting fashion in the centre.

This exhibition is organised by the @kunstpalast, Düsseldorf and will travel to the Museum für Kunst und Gewerbe, Hamburg (Summer 2020), the Hessisches Landesmuseum, Darmstadt (Fall 2020) and to MADRE in Naples (Spring 2021)

To document the first exhibition curated by Peter Lindbergh himself, TASCHEN is releasing its companion publication 'Untold Stories'. This XL volume presents more than 150 photographs from the early 1980s to the present,  that will offer new and unexpected comprehension of his considerable work.

An extensive conversation between Lindbergh and Kunstpalast Director Felix Krämer, as well as an homage by close friend Wim Wenders will offer fresh insights into the making of this collection. 
The result is an intimate and personal statement by Lindbergh about his own oeuvre.

Opening in two weeks, 'Peter Lindbergh: Untold Stories' is the first ever survey exhibition curated by Peter Lindbergh himself.

Peter spent two years working on an uncompromising collection of 140 photographs that will offer a deep insight into his extensive oeuvre, spanning from the early 1980’s to the present day.
